properties.text: World Cup: Playing in front of 93,000 spectators at Wembley (including the Queen), England beat West Germany to win the World Cup in 1966.
The 'Swinging Sixties' saw a cultural explosion of British music and fashion. Social changes also gathered pace with the passing of the Race Relations Act and the decriminalisation of homosexuality.

The Beatles: Gaining popularity with 'Love Me Do' in 1962, the Liverpool lads topped the charts for much of the decade, until their breakup in 1970. The Beatles are the best-selling music artists of all time, with 600 million record sales.

The Sun: Published for the first time in 1964, the newspaper was billed as a 'radical' alternative to The Mirror. Later it would be bought by Rupert Murdoch and become the UK's most popular newspaper across the week.
